  "prompt": "If time slows down as you approach the speed of light, then what time scale is light on?",
  "response": "According to the theory of relativity, as an object approaches the speed of light, time for that object appears to slow down relative to an outside observer. In the case of light itself, which travels at the speed of light (approximately \\(299,792,458\\) meters per second in a vacuum), the concept of time as we understand it does not apply. \n\nFrom the perspective of a photon (a particle of light), time does not pass at all. This means that if you could hypothetically experience traveling at the speed of light, you would not age or experience the passage of time. Thus, for light, the \"time scale\" is effectively nonexistent; it does not experience time.\n\nIn summary, for light, time does not elapse, and any frame of reference moving at the speed of light does not have a time scale in the conventional sense.",
